			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2016</a> paper:</span><br><i>The IDE Portability Problem and Its Solution in Monto</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/SvenKeidel.html">Sven Keidel</a>, <a href="../profile/WulfPfeiffer.html">Wulf Pfeiffer</a>, <a href="../profile/SebastianErdweg.html">Sebastian Erdweg</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/2997364.2997368">10.1145/2997364.2997368</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagM">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> Monto is infrastructure for building reusable language services across IDEs (workbench/IDE tooling).
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t2d.html"><span class="tagL">T2D: Deployment</span></a><ul><li> The central problem is portability of language tooling across different IDE deployments.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3f.html"><span class="tagL">T3F: API</span></a><ul><li> The solution relies on well-defined interfaces/APIs for composing and reusing language services.
</li></ul></li></ul>
